class Solution {
    public int minLength(String s) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(s);
        boolean changed;
        do {
            changed = false;
            for (int i = 0; i < sb.length() - 1; i++) {
                char c1 = sb.charAt(i);
                char c2 = sb.charAt(i + 1);
                if ((c1 == 'A' && c2 == 'B') || (c1 == 'C' && c2 == 'D')) {
                    sb.delete(i, i + 2);
                    changed = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
        } while (changed);
        return sb.length();
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^2)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a StringBuilder to repeatedly scan left-to-right, removing the first "AB" or "CD" encountered and restarting the scan after each deletion. This greedy approach guarantees the minimal length because any removable pair is eliminated as soon as it appears, preventing later overlaps.

